{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652360"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:35:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:35:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18534"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18534"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11266"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79748"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11266"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18534"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65052"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"10787"},{"type":"tags","id":"10788"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26121"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26130"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79748"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EViral vectors are tools used in gene therapy to deliver therapeutic genetic material to target cells. Different types of viral vectors have been developed, each with distinct properties.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a key characteristic of viral vectors used in gene therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["They maintain complete viral genomes intact","They are modified to remove pathogenic elements","They require functional viral replication","They exclusively transport bacterial DNA","They specifically target malignant cells"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key characteristic of viral vectors is that they are \u003Cstrong\u003Emodified to remove pathogenic elements\u003C/strong\u003E while retaining their ability to enter cells and deliver genetic material. This engineering makes them safe and effective tools for gene therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey maintain complete viral genomes intact\u003C/strong\u003E - Most viral genes are removed to prevent viral replication and disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey require functional viral replication\u003C/strong\u003E - Viral vectors are engineered particles that lack the ability to replicate\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey exclusively transport bacterial DNA\u003C/strong\u003E - Viral vectors are specifically designed to carry and deliver therapeutic genes from various sources\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey specifically target malignant cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Viral vectors can be designed to target various cell types, not just cancer cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis fundamental modification of removing pathogenic elements while maintaining cellular entry and gene delivery capabilities is what makes viral vectors useful tools in gene therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Viral vectors are modified viruses used to deliver therapeutic genes to target cells.","Different viral vectors (lentivirus, adenovirus, adeno-associated virus) have distinct advantages and limitations.","Key considerations for viral vectors include genetic payload capacity, integration ability, and immune response."],"references":["Bulcha JT, Wang Y, Ma H, Tai PWL, Gao G. Viral vector platforms within the gene therapy landscape. Signal Transduct Target Ther. 2021 Feb 8;6(1):53. doi: 10.1038/s41392-021-00487-6. PMID: 33558455; PMCID: PMC7868676. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33558455/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65052"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18534"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65052"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T14:23:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T14:23:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11266"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79748"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4945"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:53+10:3